JS String Methods:

#) Basic string methods:
    - Javascript strings are primitive and immutable: All string methods produce a new string without
        altering the original string.

        String length               // returns a length of a string.

        String charAt()             // returns the character at a specified index(position) in a string. 

        String charCodeAt()         // returns the code of the character at a specified index in a string.

        String codePointAt()        // returns the code point value at the specified index in a string.

        String concat()             // joins two or more strings.

        String at()                 // returns an idexed element from a string.

        String [ ]                  // returns an indexed element from a string.

        String slice()              // extracts a part of a string and returns the extracted part in a new 
                                        string.

        String substring()          // similar to slice. difference is that start and end values less than
                                        0 are treated as 0

        String substr()             // similar to slice. difference is that the second parameter specifies
                                        the length of the extracted part.
                                        ‚ö†Ô∏è substr() method is removed (deprecated) in the latest JavaScript
                                        standard.


        String toUpperCase()        // string is converted to upper case 

        String toLowerCase()        // string is converted to lower case 

        String isWellFormed()       // returns true if a string is well formed. Otherwise it returns false.
        
        String toWellFormed()       // returns a new string where all "lone surrogates" are replaced with 
                                        the Unicode replacement character (U+FFFD).

        String trim()               // removes whitespace from both sides of a string:

        String trimStart()          // works like trim(), but removes whitespace only from the start of a
                                        string.

        String trimEnd()            // like trim(), but removes whitespace only from the end of a string.
        
        String padStart()           // pads a string from the start.
        
        String padEnd()             // pads a string from the end.

        String repeat()             // returns a string with a number of copies of a string. It doesn'tag   
                                        change original string.

        String replace()            // replaces a specified value with another value in a string.

        String replaceAll()         // allows you to specify a regular expression instead of a string to
                                        be replaced

        String split()              // converts the string to an Array by splitting.    
                                        If the separator is omitted, the returned array will contain the whole
                                        string in index [0].
                                        If the separator is "", the returned array will be an array of single
                                        characters:


    üö¶Lone Surrogates:
        A lone surrogate is a Unicode surrogate code point that is not part of a valid surrogate pair used to
        represent characters in UTF-16 encoding.